```python
# Define a function to perform a perspective transform
# I've used the example grid image above to choose source points for the
# grid cell in front of the rover (each grid cell is 1 square meter in the sim)
# Define a function to perform a perspective transform
def perspect_transform(img, src, dst):
           
    M = cv2.getPerspectiveTransform(src, dst)
    warped = cv2.warpPerspective(img, M, (img.shape[1], img.shape[0]))# keep same size as input image
    
    return warped


# Define calibration box in source (actual) and destination (desired) coordinates
# These source and destination points are defined to warp the image
# to a grid where each 10x10 pixel square represents 1 square meter
# The destination box will be 2*dst_size on each side
dst_size = 5 
# Set a bottom offset to account for the fact that the bottom of the image 
# is not the position of the rover but a bit in front of it
# this is just a rough guess, feel free to change it!
bottom_offset = 6
source = np.float32([[14, 140], [301 ,140],[200, 96], [118, 96]])
destination = np.float32([[image.shape[1]/2 - dst_size, image.shape[0] - bottom_offset],
                  [image.shape[1]/2 + dst_size, image.shape[0] - bottom_offset],
                  [image.shape[1]/2 + dst_size, image.shape[0] - 2*dst_size - bottom_offset], 
                  [image.shape[1]/2 - dst_size, image.shape[0] - 2*dst_size - bottom_offset],
```

```python
# Identify pixels above the threshold
# Threshold of RGB > 160 does a nice job of identifying ground pixels only
def color_thresh(img, rgb_thresh=(160, 160, 160)):
    # Create an array of zeros same xy size as img, but single channel
    color_select = np.zeros_like(img[:,:,0])
    # Require that each pixel be above all three threshold values in RGB
    # above_thresh will now contain a boolean array with "True"
    # where threshold was met
    above_thresh = (img[:,:,0] > rgb_thresh[0]) \
                & (img[:,:,1] > rgb_thresh[1]) \
                & (img[:,:,2] > rgb_thresh[2])
    # Index the array of zeros with the boolean array and set to 1
    color_select[above_thresh] = 1
    # Return the binary image
    return color_select

threshed = color_thresh(warped)
plt.imshow(threshed, cmap='gray')
```

```python
# Invert the color threshold function to get obstacles
def get_obstacles_2(img, rgb_thresh=(160, 160, 160)):
    # Create an array of zeros same xy size as img, but single channel
    obstacles = np.zeros_like(img[:,:,0])

    below_thresh = (img[:,:,0] <= rgb_thresh[0]) \
                | (img[:,:,1] <= rgb_thresh[1]) \
                | (img[:,:,2] <= rgb_thresh[2])
    # Index the array of zeros with the boolean array and set to 1
    obstacles[below_thresh] = 1
    # Return the binary image
    return obstacles
```

```python
# get the rocks
def get_rock(img, rock_low_thresh=(0, 0, 0), rock_high_thresh=(255, 255, 255)):
    # Create an array of zeros same xy size as img, but single channel
    rock = np.zeros_like(img[:,:,0])
    # Require that each pixel be above all three threshold values in RGB
    # above_thresh will now contain a boolean array with "True"
    # where threshold was met
    above_low = (img[:,:,0] > rock_low_thresh[0]) \
                & (img[:,:,1] > rock_low_thresh[1]) \
                & (img[:,:,2] > rock_low_thresh[2])
    below_high = (img[:,:,0] < rock_high_thresh[0]) \
                & (img[:,:,1] < rock_high_thresh[1]) \
                & (img[:,:,2] < rock_high_thresh[2])
    in_range = above_low & below_high
    # Index the array of zeros with the boolean array and set to 1
    rock[in_range] = 1
    # Return the binary image
    return rock

rock_thresh_low = (160, 160, 0)
```

#### Coordinate Transformations
##### For the Test Data
Define the functions used to do coordinate transforms and apply them to an image. Use a random image from the `test_dataset` folder


```python
# Define a function to convert from image coords to rover coords
def rover_coords(binary_img):
    # Identify nonzero pixels
    ypos, xpos = binary_img.nonzero()
    # Calculate pixel positions with reference to the rover position being at the 
    # center bottom of the image.  
    x_pixel = -(ypos - binary_img.shape[0]).astype(np.float)
    y_pixel = -(xpos - binary_img.shape[1]/2 ).astype(np.float)
    return x_pixel, y_pixel

# Define a function to convert to radial coords in rover space
def to_polar_coords(x_pixel, y_pixel):
    # Convert (x_pixel, y_pixel) to (distance, angle) 
    # in polar coordinates in rover space
    # Calculate distance to each pixel
    dist = np.sqrt(x_pixel**2 + y_pixel**2)
    # Calculate angle away from vertical for each pixel
    angles = np.arctan2(y_pixel, x_pixel)
    return dist, angles

# Define a function to map rover space pixels to world space
def rotate_pix(xpix, ypix, yaw):
    # Convert yaw to radians
    yaw_rad = yaw * np.pi / 180
    xpix_rotated = (xpix * np.cos(yaw_rad)) - (ypix * np.sin(yaw_rad))
                            
    ypix_rotated = (xpix * np.sin(yaw_rad)) + (ypix * np.cos(yaw_rad))
    # Return the result  
    return xpix_rotated, ypix_rotated

def translate_pix(xpix_rot, ypix_rot, xpos, ypos, scale): 
    # Apply a scaling and a translation
    xpix_translated = (xpix_rot / scale) + xpos
    ypix_translated = (ypix_rot / scale) + ypos
    # Return the result  
    return xpix_translated, ypix_translated


# Define a function to apply rotation and translation (and clipping)
# Once you define the two functions above this function should work
def pix_to_world(xpix, ypix, xpos, ypos, yaw, world_size, scale):
    # Apply rotation
    xpix_rot, ypix_rot = rotate_pix(xpix, ypix, yaw)
    # Apply translation
    xpix_tran, ypix_tran = translate_pix(xpix_rot, ypix_rot, xpos, ypos, scale)
    # Perform rotation, translation and clipping all at once
    x_pix_world = np.clip(np.int_(xpix_tran), 0, world_size - 1)
    y_pix_world = np.clip(np.int_(ypix_tran), 0, world_size - 1)
    # Return the result
    return x_pix_world, y_pix_world

# Grab another random image
path = '../test_dataset/IMG/*'
img_list = glob.glob(path) 
idx = np.random.randint(0, len(img_list)-1)
image = mpimg.imread(img_list[idx])
warped = perspect_transform(image, source, destination)
threshed = color_thresh(warped)

# Calculate pixel values in rover-centric coords and distance/angle to all pixels
xpix, ypix = rover_coords(threshed)
dist, angles = to_polar_coords(xpix, ypix)
mean_dir = np.mean(angles)

# Do some plotting
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,9))
plt.subplot(221)
plt.imshow(image)
plt.subplot(222)
plt.imshow(warped)
plt.subplot(223)
plt.imshow(threshed, cmap='gray')
plt.subplot(224)
plt.plot(xpix, ypix, '.')
plt.ylim(-160, 160)
plt.xlim(0, 160)
arrow_length = 100
x_arrow = arrow_length * np.cos(mean_dir)
y_arrow = arrow_length * np.sin(mean_dir)
plt.arrow(0, 0, x_arrow, y_arrow, color='red', zorder=2, head_width=10, width=2)


```

#### Write a function to process stored images

The completed function is shown below. The scale for the world map is 10, the same as in lesson. The source and destination points for the perspective transform are the global ones defined above. 

Note that the navigable, obstacles and rock images are all single channel images, and need to be stacked before rendering. 

Another point worth noting is the sequence of the processing. The sequence shown here is performing the perspective transform first, then apply color threshold and coordinates conversion. But as pointed out in the livestream discussion, **it's better to perform color threshold before the perspective tranform**, so I used the latter sequence in my final implementation for the autonomous mode.

### Autonomous Navigation and Mapping
#### Fill in the perception_step() (at the bottom of the perception.py script) and decision_step() (in decision.py) functions in the autonomous mapping scripts and an explanation is provided in the writeup of how and why these functions were modified as they were.
#### Function: perception_step()
Here as I mentioned above, the first step is to apply color threshold to the incoming image to get navigable terrain, obstacles and rock samples. Then using the same source and destination points defined above, perform perspective transform on them, and fill into Rover.vision_image to be displayed as the rover vision on the left of the simulator screen. 

Secondly, convert to rover-centric coordinates for the navigation. One trick that I learned from the Udacity expert is to only use a small portion of the navigable image, the front center to be precise, instead of the whole one. 

The next step is to convert the pixel values to a world coordinates and fill the world map. As mentioned in lesson 14, section "Optimizing Map Fidelity Tip", the current roll and pitch of the rover should be filtered, and feed in the world map only when these two and nearly zero, since only those data obtained during then are valid.  

Finally, the navigable pixels need to be converted to polar coordinates. The rock pixels are also converted and stored in the Rover instance, so when a rock appears in the nearby view, the rover can navigate to it and pick it up.


```python
# Apply the above functions in succession and update the Rover state accordingly
def perception_step(Rover):
    # Perform perception steps to update Rover()
    # TODO: 
    # NOTE: camera image is coming to you in Rover.img

    # Get the image
    rover_img = Rover.img

    # 1) Apply color threshold to identify navigable terrain/obstacles/rock samples
    navigable = color_thresh(rover_img)
    obstacles = get_obstacles_1(rover_img)
    rock_thresh_low = (160, 160, 0)
    rock_thresh_high = (255, 255, 140)
    rock = get_rock(rover_img, rock_thresh_low, rock_thresh_high)

    # 2) Define source and destination points for perspective transform
    # These source and destination points are defined to warp the image
    # to a grid where each 10x10 pixel square represents 1 square meter

    # Define source point
    source = np.float32([[14, 140], [301, 140], [200, 96], [118, 96]])
    # The destination box will be 2*dst_size on each side
    dst_size = 5
    # Set a bottom offset to account for the fact that the bottom of the image 
    # is not the position of the rover but a bit in front of it
    # this is just a rough guess, feel free to change it!
    bottom_offset = 6

    # 3) Apply perspective transform
    destination = np.float32([[rover_img.shape[1] / 2 - dst_size, rover_img.shape[0] - bottom_offset],
                              [rover_img.shape[1] / 2 + dst_size, rover_img.shape[0] - bottom_offset],
                              [rover_img.shape[1] / 2 + dst_size, rover_img.shape[0] - 2 * dst_size - bottom_offset],
                              [rover_img.shape[1] / 2 - dst_size, rover_img.shape[0] - 2 * dst_size - bottom_offset],
                              ])
    navi_warped = perspect_transform(navigable, source, destination)
    obstacles_warped = perspect_transform(obstacles, source, destination)
    rock_warped = perspect_transform(rock, source, destination)

    # 4) Update Rover.vision_image (this will be displayed on left side of screen)
    # Example: Rover.vision_image[:,:,0] = obstacle color-thresholded binary image
    #          Rover.vision_image[:,:,1] = rock_sample color-thresholded binary image
    #          Rover.vision_image[:,:,2] = navigable terrain color-thresholded binary image

    Rover.vision_image[:, :, 0] = obstacles_warped * 255
    Rover.vision_image[:, :, 1] = rock_warped * 255
    Rover.vision_image[:, :, 2] = navi_warped * 255

    # 5) Convert map image pixel values to rover-centric coords
    # limit the view of the navi image to get better result
    row1 = np.int(rover_img.shape[0] - dst_size * 5)
    row2 = np.int(rover_img.shape[0] - bottom_offset)
    col1 = np.int(rover_img.shape[1] / 2 - dst_size * 4)
    col2 = np.int(rover_img.shape[1] / 2 + dst_size * 4)

    front_navi = navi_warped[row1:row2, col1:col2]
    nav_xpix, nav_ypix = rover_coords(front_navi)
    obs_xpix, obs_ypix = rover_coords(obstacles_warped)
    rock_xpix, rock_ypix = rover_coords(rock_warped)

    # 6) Convert rover-centric pixel values to world coordinates
    # get current x, y and yaw for the world coords mapping
    xp = Rover.pos[0]
    yp = Rover.pos[1]
    yaw = Rover.yaw
    scale = 10

    nav_x_world, nav_y_world = pix_to_world(nav_xpix, nav_ypix, xp,
                                            yp, yaw,
                                            Rover.worldmap.shape[0], scale)
    obs_x_world, obs_y_world = pix_to_world(obs_xpix, obs_ypix, xp,
                                            yp, yaw,
                                            Rover.worldmap.shape[0], scale)
    rock_x_world, rock_y_world = pix_to_world(rock_xpix, rock_ypix, xp,
                                              yp, yaw,
                                              Rover.worldmap.shape[0], scale)

    # 7) Update Rover worldmap (to be displayed on right side of screen)
    # Example: Rover.worldmap[obstacle_y_world, obstacle_x_world, 0] += 1
    #          Rover.worldmap[rock_y_world, rock_x_world, 1] += 1
    #          Rover.worldmap[navigable_y_world, navigable_x_world, 2] += 1
    # filter the rover state
    roll = Rover.roll
    pitch = Rover.pitch

    if (roll > 359.5 or roll < 0.5) and (pitch < 0.5 or pitch > 359.5):
        Rover.worldmap[obs_y_world, obs_x_world, 0] += 1
        Rover.worldmap[rock_y_world, rock_x_world, 1] += 1
        Rover.worldmap[nav_y_world, nav_x_world, 2] += 1

    # 8) Convert rover-centric pixel positions to polar coordinates
    # Update Rover pixel distances and angles
    rover_centric_pixel_distances, rover_centric_angles = to_polar_coords(nav_xpix, nav_ypix)

    Rover.nav_dists = rover_centric_pixel_distances
    Rover.nav_angles = rover_centric_angles

    # Note down rock pos in view
    rock_distances, rock_angles = to_polar_coords(rock_xpix, rock_ypix)

    Rover.rock_dists = rock_distances
    Rover.rock_angles = rock_angles

    return Rover
```

I have also added a function to check the rocks in nearby view when the rover is moving forward. 

It's worth noting that the range of the rock detection needs to be fine-tuned. If it's too wide, the rover will be easily distracted off its course by a rock sample across the valley. This seems to be fine, but considering the fact that the rover will eventually travel to the other side of the valley and pick up the samples on that side, this "wandering-on-and-off-track" action is actually a waste of time . 

On the other hand, if it's too narrnow, some of the rocks will be hard to spot by the rover, especially those hidding behind a large obstacle. The rover will usually miss them since its view will be blocked by the obstacle and once it's cleared from it, the view angle of the rover will be far away from the sample, hence the rover will miss it. After many rounds of try and error, I settled it at 50. 


```python
# Define a function to check the rocks in view
def check_rocks(Rover):
    if len(Rover.rock_angles):  # there's rock
        if np.mean(Rover.rock_dists) < 50:
            return True
    return False
```

#### Function: decision_step()
I have extracted the main decision making process into another function, leaving only two print statements for the debugging.


```python
# This is where you can build a decision tree for determining throttle, brake and steer
# commands based on the output of the perception_step() function
def decision_step(Rover):
    # Implement conditionals to decide what to do given perception data
    # Here you're all set up with some basic functionality but you'll need to
    # improve on this decision tree to do a good job of navigating autonomously!

    # Example:
    # Check if we have vision data to make decisions with
    if Rover.nav_angles is not None:
        # print some info for debugging

        print("throttle_count:", Rover.throttle_count)

        make_decision(Rover)

    # Just to make the rover do something
    # even if no modifications have been made to the code
    else:
        Rover.throttle = Rover.throttle_set[0]
        Rover.steer = 0
        Rover.brake = 0

    # If in a state where want to pickup a rock send pickup command
    if Rover.near_sample and Rover.vel == 0 and not Rover.picking_up:
        Rover.send_pickup = True

    return Rover
```

In the decision making function, I have added several other modes for various purposes besides the default ones.

##### forward

This is one of the default modes and the one that the rover will be in for the most part. 

The default throttle function is too rough so I added the following one:


```python
# Set throttle for rover
def set_rover_throttle(Rover):
    if len(Rover.nav_angles) >= Rover.go_forward * 3:
        Rover.throttle += Rover.throttle_set[2]
    elif len(Rover.nav_angles) >= Rover.go_forward * 2:
        Rover.throttle += Rover.throttle_set[1]
    elif len(Rover.nav_angles) > Rover.go_forward:
        Rover.throttle += Rover.throttle_set[0]
    else:
        Rover.throttle = 0
```

In the above function, the rover will adjust its throttle based on the current navigable terrain. To work with it, I have also changed the throttle_set in Rover class from a number into a tuple, providing 3 levels of acceleration setting: if it's wild open, then go full throttle; otherwise, adjust the throttle accordingly; if the terrain is too small to navigate, the throttle needs to be released so the rover can turn and find a movable direction.  

Seveal properties besides the default ones have also been added to the Rover class, and will be discussed along the way. 

* Rover.home is used to note the home position of the rover at the beginning of the process for the returning.


* A boolean flag, Rover.is_going_home, is used to indicate if the rover has successfully discovered and picked up all 6 samples and will return home. The following function uses this flag to generate next steer value for the rover.


```python
# Get next steer
def get_navi_steer(Rover):
    if Rover.is_going_home:
        # get home pos
        home = Rover.home
        # get current rover pos
        pos = Rover.pos
        # convert them into world coords
        home_world_x, home_world_y = pix_to_world(home[0], home[1], pos[0], pos[1], Rover.yaw, Rover.worldmap.shape[0],
                                                  10)
        home_world_dist, home_world_angle = to_polar_coords(home_world_x, home_world_y)

        mean_angle = np.mean(Rover.nav_angles)

        # Steer toward home
        if mean_angle > home_world_angle:
            steer = -10
        else:
            steer = +10
    else:
        # Set steering to average angle clipped to the range +/- 15
        steer = np.mean(Rover.nav_angles * 180 / np.pi) + 14.9  # lean towards left side wall

    return np.clip(steer, -15, 15)
```

If the rover is going home, then the steer will be set toward a direction that aligns the rover camera with the home position; otherwise, the steer will be set to be the mean value of the navigable angles plus 14.9 degree, cliped within +/-15 degree. 

The offset of 14.9 makes the rover **a "wall crawler" towards the left wall**. As mentioned in lesson 14, section "Optimizing for Finding All Rocks Tip", this would help with the fidelity and rock finding. 

* The brake of the rover has been divided into a soft and hard one. When the rover is maintaining speed or needs to make a wide turn, use the soft brake to reduce the speed gently; otherwise use the hard brake to stop the rover immediately. The following function is used to maintain the rover speed within a set range. 


```python
# Maintain a certain speed
def rover_maintain_speed(Rover, min, max):
    if Rover.vel > max:
        Rover.throttle = 0
        Rover.brake = Rover.brake_soft
    elif Rover.vel < min:
        Rover.throttle = Rover.throttle_set[1]
        Rover.brake = 0
    else:
        Rover.throttle = 0
        Rover.brake = 0
```

##### decelerate
In `forward` mode, if the rover finds that the navigable terrain drops below a certain threshold, it will switch to `decelerate` mode and slow down. 
* Rover.decelerate_forward is the threshold below which the rover will slow down.

##### approach
When moving in `forward` mode, the rover will also look for rock samples in nearby view, and if one is spotted, it will slow down, and switch to `approach` mode.

In this mode, if the rover is near a sample, it will stop and switch to `pickup` mode and pick the sample up; otherwise, it will adjust its speed based on the distance with the rock, and turn towards the rock slowly. Another check_stuck() function is used here with a higher threshold in case the rover is stuck when trying to reach a rock that is placed at some weird angle.  

##### pickup
Once the rover finishes approaching, it will switch to this mode and pick the rock up. After picking, the rover will switch to `stop` mode and as long as there's more rocks to be discovered, it will start looking for navigable terrain. 

##### stop
This is the default stop mode with one extra condition added: Rover.is_done. 
* Rover.is_done indicates if the current rover position is close enough with the noted home position. Once this flag is raised, the rover will switch to stop mode and won't be looking for navigable terrain.

##### unstuck
Sometimes, the rover will stuck against an obstacle, or making circles because the steer is locked to +/-15 degree. The following two functions checks for stuck and circling situation. 
* Rover.throttle_count, Rover.circle_time and Rover.forward_count are all counters to help the rover get unstuck. 
    
    By default, as long as the throttle is set, the rover's velocity will increase. Whenever the throttle is set above a threshold but the velocity is not increasing, the throttle_count will begin counting. Once it reaches a certain threshold, the rover will save its current mode and switch to `unstuck` mode. In this mode, the rover will release throttle and brake, turn a small degree using the 4-wheel turn, and tries to speed up along the current direction. If it can move, the rover will switch to the saved mode and continue; otherwise, the rover will repeat this process until it can move. 
    
    In a rare case though, this method won't work since the throttle cannot be set and the speed won't increase. The rover will just sit there still, idling. In such a case, another counter, Rover.forwar_count will kick in and begin count, and help the rover get unstuck using the same process as above.
    
    Besides stuck, another problem is circling. Once the rover locks the steer at +/-15 degree for too long, this counter will be triggered and indicates that the rover is circling around without making any progress, and needs to switch to `unstuck` mode. 
    
    
* Rover.stuck_time note down the beginning time of the unstuck process so the rover won't be in this mode turnning around forever.


* Rover.last_mode saves the last mode the rover is in before switching into the `unstuck` mode, so that the rover can resume its action after it's free.


```python
# Check if the rover is stuck
def check_stuck(Rover, threshold):
    # Throttle is on but the rover is not speeding up
    if Rover.throttle >= 0.1 and Rover.vel < 0.2:  # stuck
        if Rover.throttle_count > threshold:
            Rover.throttle_count = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = True
            Rover.stuck_time = Rover.total_time
            Rover.last_mode = Rover.mode  # save the last mode
            Rover.mode = 'unstuck'
        else:
            Rover.throttle_count += Rover.throttle_set[1]
    # Rover is running
    elif Rover.vel >= 0.2:
        Rover.is_stuck = False
        Rover.throttle_count = 0
    # For the strange situation when throttle cannot be set in forward mode
    elif Rover.mode == 'forward' and Rover.vel < 0.2:
        if Rover.forward_count > 1000:
            Rover.forward_count = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = True
            Rover.stuck_time = Rover.total_time
            Rover.last_mode = Rover.mode  # save the last mode
            Rover.mode = 'unstuck'
        else:
            Rover.forward_count += 1


# Check if the rover is making circle
def check_circle(Rover):
    if Rover.steer == 15 and Rover.vel > 0.5:
        # circling
        if Rover.circle_time > 50:
            Rover.circle_time = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = True
            Rover.stuck_time = Rover.total_time
            Rover.last_mode = Rover.mode  # save the last mode
            Rover.mode = 'unstuck'
        elif Rover.steer != 15:
            Rover.circle_time = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = False
            Rover.stuck_time = 0
        else:
            Rover.circle_time += 0.2
    elif Rover.steer == -15 and Rover.vel > 0.5:
        # circling
        if Rover.circle_time > 50:
            Rover.circle_time = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = True
            Rover.stuck_time = Rover.total_time
            Rover.last_mode = Rover.mode  # save the last mode
            Rover.mode = 'unstuck'
        elif Rover.steer != -15:
            Rover.circle_time = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = False
            Rover.stuck_time = 0
        else:
            Rover.circle_time += 0.2
```

The following function is the main decision tree. 
* Rover.last_steer is used to save the last steer value, so that if a steer change is larger than a set threshold, the rover will slow down first to make the turn as smooth as possible.


```python
def make_decision(Rover):
    # Check for Rover.mode status
    # Forward
    if Rover.mode == 'forward':
        if Rover.home is None:
            # note down home pos
            Rover.home = Rover.pos
        
        # all rocks been found, let's go home
        if Rover.samples_found == 6:
            Rover.is_going_home = True

        # close enough, rover is home
        if Rover.is_going_home:
            if (Rover.pos[0] - Rover.home[0] < 0.5) and (Rover.pos[1] - Rover.home[1] < 0.5):
                Rover.is_done = True
                Rover.is_going_home = False
                Rover.mode = 'stop'

        # Check the extent of navigable terrain
        if len(Rover.nav_angles) >= Rover.stop_forward:
            # If mode is forward, navigable terrain looks good
            # and velocity is below max, then throttle
            if Rover.vel < Rover.max_vel:
                # keep accelerating
                set_rover_throttle(Rover)
            else:  # Else coast
                Rover.throttle = 0
            Rover.brake = 0

            # Get new steer value
            new_steer = get_navi_steer(Rover)

            # If the steer difference is large, slow it down
            if np.absolute(Rover.last_steer - new_steer) > 3:
                Rover.throttle = 0
                Rover.brake = Rover.brake_soft

            # Steer the rover and save the steer value
            Rover.steer = new_steer
            Rover.last_steer = new_steer

        # If there's a decrease of navigable terrain pixels then go to 'decelerate' mode
        elif len(Rover.nav_angles) < Rover.decelerate_forward:
            # Set mode to "decelerate" and hit the brakes!
            Rover.throttle = 0
            # Set brake to stored brake value
            if Rover.vel > 1:
                Rover.brake = Rover.brake_soft
            else:  # coast
                Rover.brake = 0
            Rover.mode = 'decelerate'

        check_stuck(Rover, 30)
        check_circle(Rover)

        if check_rocks(Rover):  # got rocks
            if Rover.vel > 1:
                Rover.throttle = 0
                Rover.brake = Rover.brake_soft
            elif Rover.vel < 0.5:
                Rover.throttle = Rover.throttle_set[0]
                Rover.brake = 0
            else:
                Rover.throttle = 0
                Rover.brake = 0
                Rover.mode = 'approach'

    # Not enough available terrain in front, need to slow down
    elif Rover.mode == 'decelerate':
        # If there's a lack of navigable terrain pixels then go to 'stop' mode
        if len(Rover.nav_angles) < Rover.stop_forward:
            # Set mode to "stop" and hit the brakes!
            Rover.throttle = 0
            # Set brake to stored brake value
            Rover.brake = Rover.brake_hard
            Rover.steer = 0
            Rover.mode = 'stop'
        elif len(Rover.nav_angles) >= Rover.go_forward:
            # Set throttle back to stored value
            Rover.throttle = Rover.throttle_set[0]
            # Release the brake
            Rover.brake = 0
            Rover.mode = 'forward'

    # To get the rover out of a stuck situation
    elif Rover.mode == 'unstuck':
        # Release throttle
        Rover.throttle = 0
        # Stop the rover first
        if Rover.vel > 0.2:
            Rover.brake = Rover.brake_hard
        else:
            # Release the brake to allow turning
            Rover.brake = 0

        # get current time
        time_now = Rover.total_time
        # spin a little
        if time_now > Rover.stuck_time + 0.5:
            Rover.steer = 0
            Rover.is_stuck = False
            Rover.stuck_time = 0
            # try move
            Rover.mode = 'test_run'
        else:
            Rover.steer = -15

    # Try to move along current direction
    elif Rover.mode == 'test_run':
        # Full throttle
        Rover.throttle = Rover.throttle_set[2]

        if Rover.throttle >= 0.1 and Rover.vel < 0.2:
            # Still stuck, need to turn again
            if Rover.throttle_count > 30:
                Rover.throttle_count = 0
                Rover.stuck_time = Rover.total_time
                Rover.mode = 'unstuck'
            else:
                Rover.throttle_count += Rover.throttle_set[1]
        elif Rover.vel >= 0.2:
            # this direction is movable
            Rover.mode = Rover.last_mode

    # Got rock in sight, approach it
    elif Rover.mode == 'approach':
        # Near sample, stop the rover and pick it up
        if Rover.near_sample:
            Rover.throttle = 0
            Rover.brake = Rover.brake_hard
            # If in a state where want to pickup a rock send pickup command
            if Rover.vel == 0:
                Rover.mode = 'pickup'
        else:
            # Right beside the rock, turn the rover to get a good angle
            if np.mean(Rover.rock_dists) < 2:
                rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 0, 0.2)
                if np.mean(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi > 0:
                    Rover.steer = 15
                elif np.mean(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi < 0:
                    Rover.steer = -15
            else:
                # Adjust speed based on the dist with the rock
                if np.mean(Rover.rock_dists) > 30:
                    rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 1.7, 2)
                elif np.mean(Rover.rock_dists) > 20:
                    rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 1.4, 1.7)
                elif np.mean(Rover.rock_dists) > 10:
                    rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 1, 1.4)
                else:
                    rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 0.6, 1)

                # Turn the rover towards the rock
                try:
                    if (np.max(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi >= -180) \
                            and (np.max(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi <= 180):
                        Rover.steer = np.max(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi
                    else:
                        rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 0.1, 0.3)
                        if np.mean(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi > 0:
                            Rover.steer = 15
                        elif np.mean(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi < 0:
                            Rover.steer = -15
                except ValueError:
                    rover_maintain_speed(Rover, 0.1, 0.3)
                    if np.mean(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi > 0:
                        Rover.steer = 15
                    elif np.mean(Rover.rock_angles) * 180 / np.pi < 0:
                        Rover.steer = -15

        # Check if the rover is stuck with a longer waiting time
        check_stuck(Rover, 100)

    # Pick up the rock
    elif Rover.mode == 'pickup':
        # If in a state where want to pickup a rock send pickup command
        if Rover.near_sample and not Rover.picking_up:
            Rover.send_pickup = True
        elif Rover.picking_up:
            Rover.mode = 'stop'

    # If we're already in "stop" mode then make different decisions
    elif Rover.mode == 'stop':
        # If we're in stop mode but still moving keep braking
        if Rover.vel > 0.2:
            Rover.throttle = 0
            Rover.brake = Rover.brake_hard
            Rover.steer = 0
        # If we're not moving (vel < 0.2) then do something else
        else:
            if not Rover.is_done:  # if done (returned with all 6 rocks), no longer looking for sufficient terrain
                # Now we're stopped and we have vision data to see if there's a path forward
                nav_ang_len = len(Rover.nav_angles)
                if nav_ang_len < Rover.go_forward:
                    Rover.throttle = 0
                    # Release the brake to allow turning
                    Rover.brake = 0
                    # Turn range is +/- 15 degrees, when stopped the next line will induce 4-wheel turning
                    # if Rover.steer > 0:
                    Rover.steer = -15
                    # else: # wrong direction
                    #    Rover.steer = -15
                # If we're stopped but see sufficient navigable terrain in front then go!
                if nav_ang_len >= Rover.go_forward:
                    # Set throttle back to stored value
                    Rover.throttle = Rover.throttle_set[0]
                    # Release the brake
                    Rover.brake = 0
                    Rover.steer = 0
                    Rover.mode = 'forward'
```

### Improvements  
There's still huge space for improvements. The following are some of the most important ones that were not implemented yet due to the lack of time and technique.

* Performance

    1. Navigation
    
    For now, my way to navigate the rover is to compute the average value for the navigable angles, and add a fix offset to make it a "wall crawler". This works most of the time but clearly it's not the best way. 
    
    One improvement I can think of is to dynamically adjust this offset by using the angle that shifts most from the mean value, but I cannot get it to work properly. 
    
    2. Obstacles Identification
    
    The way the rover identifies obstacles now is to simply inverse the navigable terrain, which is very rough. And also it cannot distinguish those large piles of rocks on the ground from the moutains, only categories them all into "no-go-zone". 
    
    I tried to add a second layer of detection for the large rocks but it will make the rover too sensitive for the edge to be a "wall crawler", thus have to leave it as is.  
    
    3. Rock Sample Identification
    
    The current rock detection works fine, but in some rare cases it will fail and note a certain point on the map as a sample, which is impossible to reach, and the rover will try forver to go to that point. 
    
    As noted in the notebook, there are better ways to perform better identification using external libraries, like OpenCV, and help alleviate this problem. 
    
    4. Get Unstuck
    
    As explained earlier, the rover sometimes gets stuck against an obstacle or the wall. To get unstuck, my current way is to stop the rover, do a 4 wheel turn to the right for a small angle, then try to move forward. If it cannot move, then repeat the process. This works, but appearly is inefficient. Sometimes there will be a wide open space on the left side of the rover, and if it turn left, it will get out easily. 
    
    An obvious update to this method is to compute the navigable terrain on the left and right side of the rover, and compare them; if the terrain on the right is larger than the one on the left, turn right, and vice versa. This will save a huge amount of time wasted on the unstuck efforts.  
    
    5. Return Home
    
    My current implementation of the returning is very primal: note down the home position at the beginning of the process, and when the rover is ready to go home, just compare the angle of the home position in the world map and the one of the rover, and then steer the rover toward that angle within the navigable terrain. More than often the rover will be blocked by an obstacle trying to steer at an impossible angle, or just bang against the wall forever because the home position is behind it. 
    
    I have tried to implement an algorithm that computes the angle and distance differences between the home position and the current rover position, but failed to make it work.
    
    
* Feature
    1. Remember the Route
    
    Currently my rover doesn't have any memory for the route. It will roam forever on the map along the wall edge until all samples has been collected. 
    
    A better algorithm is needed to store the way points for the navigation so repeatitive mapping can be avoided.
    
    2. Remember the Rocks
    
    Occasionally, the rover will miss a certain rock sample because of the detection range mentioned before. It would help a lot if the rover can remember the locations of the samples and mark one as missed or failed, so the rover can go to it directly if all others are found. 
    
    3. `Reset` Mode
    
    Add a delicated mode to handle exceptions and reset the rover to its normal working status. The `unstuck` mode serves this purpose partially but is not enough. 
    
    4. Faster and Smoother
    
    As mentioned in lesson 14, the speed of the rover is another key aspect that can be improved. I tried to increase the travel speed but it will significantly lower the smoothness of the driving and hence jeopardize the quality of the mapping.  
    
    5. Other Criterias For "Job Done"
    
    Right now, the only flag for the rover to stop roaming is that all 6 samples has been picked. It would be much better if some other criterias can be used besides this, like the percentage of the mapping, the total mission time, etc., otherwise the rover will wander forever if there is even just 1 sample missing. 
    
    6. Dynamic Rock Detection Range
    
    With the other criterias set above, the rock detection range discussed before can be dynamically adjusted for a more efficient discovery. 
    
    When the mission begins, the rock detection range can be set tightly so only those rocks near the rover route will be discovered and picked, avoiding distraction from the other side of the valley; once the majority of the map has been searched (say, 70%) but there are still samples to be found, increase the rock detection range so the rover can see farther.

    7. Timeout For Each Mode
    
    For now, there is no way to control how long the rover should stay in each mode. A timeout should be added so that if a certain action takes too long, the rover can be reset.
    
    8. Richer Display
    
    Add display to the simulator screen so the current information and status of the rover can be seen.
